    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Development and Validation of Liquid Chromatographic Methods For The</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Tirumala Rajesh</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Liquid Chromatographic<br />Anti-Diabetic Drugs</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Oct-2010 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0018</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">The thesis deals with the studies on the “Development and validation of
liquid chromatographic methods for the quantification of anti-diabetic drugs in
formulations and biological samples”. Today analysis entails much more than the
analysis of active pharmaceutical ingredients or the formulated product. The
number of drugs introduced into the market is increasing every year. These drugs
may be either new entities or partial structural modifications of the existing ones.
Very often, there is a time lag from the date of introduction of a drug into the
market to the date of its inclusion in pharmacopoeias. This happens because of the
possible uncertainties in the continuous and wider usage of these drugs, reports of
new toxicities (resulting in their withdrawal from the market), development of
patient resistance and introduction of better drugs by competitors. Under these
conditions, standards and analytical procedures for these drugs may not be
available in pharmacopoeias. It becomes necessary, therefore, to develop newer
analytical methods for such drugs.
The details about the drug discovery and development, the need for drug
analysis, chromatographic methodology (method development and optimization)
and experimental results of drug quantification in dosage forms, biological matrix
and validation of the methods were given.
ix
The aim of the study is to develop simple, sensitive, precise and accurate
methods for the quantification of selected anti-diabetic drugs in single, multicomponent
dosage forms and also in biological matrix like rat and human plasma.
Optimization of each method is carried out based on mobile phase ratio, pH of the
mobile phase, flow rate and stationary phase used.
The International Conference on Harmonization (ICH), United States- Food
and Drug Administration (US-FDA) and World Health Organization (WHO)
guidelines etc., are followed in optimization and validation of the developed
methods for there specificity and selectivity, recovery, accuracy, intra-day and
inter-day precision, robustness and short-term, long-term and freeze-thaw stability
studies. The results were given based on % CV (or % RSD) values.
One method for single drug i.e., Voglibose and five combinations of multicomponent
dosage forms were selected- 1) Metformin and Pioglitazone, 2)
Metformin and Nateglinide, 3) Pioglitazone and Glimepiride, 4) Rosiglitazone and
Gliclazide and 5) Metformin, Pioglitazone and Glimepiride. A RP-HPLC method
with ultra-violet detection (refractive index for Voglibose) was used for
development of the assay method. Acetonitrile or methanol were used as solvent
A, water, phosphate and ammonium acetate buffers at pH 3-3.5 were used as
solvent B. various combinations and mixture ratios were tried and optimized to get
good resolution and symmetric peaks. All the methods were sensitive enough to
quantify the drugs in their respective dosage forms. The calibration curves gave
good linearity and correlation coefficient (r2). The methods were subjected to
validation for recovery, accuracy, precision, robustness, selectivity and specificity
and stability as per ICH guidelines. The Mean, Standard deviation (S.D.), Relative
Standard Deviation (% RSD) and Standard Error (SE) were calculated and were
found to be within the limits.
A stability indicating HPLC method was developed to quantify Sitagliptin
in presence of its degradation products. Sitagliptin was subjected to hydrolysis
(acid and alkali), oxidation (peroxide) and exposed to sunlight, dry heat and UV
light for specified time period. The mobile phase consisting of 10 mM ammonium
acetate (pH 3.0±0.01) and methanol in the ratio of 25: 75 resolved drug from
degradation products. Hydrolysis of the drug show degradation and in other
conditions mass balance was close to 99.5%. The method was also validated as per
ICH guidelines and the results were found to be satisfactory. Specificity and peak
purity were confirmed using Photo Diode Array (PDA) detector peaks.
A simultaneous quantification for five Anti-diabetic drugs in formulations
and human plasma was carried out along with five methods for the quantification
of selected Anti-diabetic drugs in biological matrix like rat and human plasma. RPHPLC
with UV detection (MS for Rosiglitazone) was used. Epalrestat,
Rosiglitazone and Sitagliptin were quantified separately in rat plasma. Two
methods were developed for the simultaneous quantification of Sulfonyl ureas,
Thiazolidinediones and Mitiglinide group of anti-diabetic drugs in human plasma
which includes: Glipizide, Gliclazide, Glibenclamide, Glimepiride, Metformin,
Nateglinide, Pioglitazone, Repaglinide and Rosiglitazone. Either acetonitrile or
methanol or both were used as solvent A and water, potassium dihydrogen ortho
phosphate, ammonium acetate, formic acid, triethylamine and ortho phosphoric
acid combinations were used as solvent B in different ratios to optimize the
methods and Validated as per US-FDA guidelines for its specificity and
selectivity, sensitivity, recovery, precision and stability. Solid-phase, liquid-liquid
and protein precipitation techniques were used for extraction of the drugs from
plasma and results were found to be satisfactory.
The methods developed in the present study were found to be simple, rapid,
accurate, precise, specific, linear, robust/ rugged. They are thus suitable for the
quantification of selected drugs from raw materials, formulations and biological
matrix. The newly developed methods may be used in, Research institutions,
Quality control departments in industries, Approved testing laboratories,
Biopharmaceutics and Bio-equivalence studies, Clinical pharmacokinetic studies
and Therapeutic drug monitoring studies.</td></tr>
